sion Tube 2 style suspension with improved toe-in was used.  Tucker #1025 and below used a mechanical linkage for the Cyclops Eye, whereas #1026 and above used a new, simpler cable design.<ref name=\"lemaymarymount.org\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1027||Unknown||Unknown||Franklin O-335||Unknown||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Waltz Blue/200\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|Car was rolled in testing at [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway]] by Tucker Corp, 1948. The engine/trans were removed at the factory, the chassis was sold at the Tucker factory auction after its closure. Museum used to own some body panels to wrecked Tucker 1018, other parts were either lost or used in restoration of other Tuckers. The car was sold by the owner of Historic Auto Attractions; current location is unknown. <ref>http://www.kustomrama.com/images/d/d0/Tucker-1027.jpg</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1028||Arundel, Maine||[[Maine Classic Car Museum]]||Franklin O-335||Cord 810/812||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Beige/400\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|Car was sold in an auction on April 27, 2019 for $1.8 million to Tim Stentiford, owner of Maine Classic Car Museum.\nTo date there are 2 Tuckers that reside in the state Maine, thus being the only one on public display in New England.<ref>https://www.djournal.com/news/star-of-tupelo-automobile-museum-goes-for-m/article_367d6912-6c46-51c0-b5fa-7075ade286e9.html</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1029||California||Privately owned||Franklin O-335||Tucker Y-1||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Grey(Silver)/500\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|Preston Tucker's personal car that he drove for seven years until he sold it in 1955 to [[Winthrop Rockefeller]]. As of October 2017 located in the Lew Webb's Classic Car Museum in Aliso Viejo, CA. <ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u6jzCdESDrc</ref><ref>http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/buying-maintenance/a14498169/buy-preston-tuckers-personal-tucker-48/</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carscoops.com/2017/12/preston-tuckers-personal-car-is-true/|title=Preston Tucker\u2019s Person