\"| 1036||Nevada||Privately owned||Franklin O-335||Tucker Y-1||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Maroon/600\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|Tucker #1036 was sold at [[RM Sotheby's]] Auction in [[Monterey, California|Monterey]] on August 15, 2014 for $1,567,500.<ref name=\"AUCTION4\">[http://www.rmsothebys.com/lots/lot.cfm?lot_id=1067570 RM Sotheby's Auctions - 1948 Tucker 48, #1036], Retrieved March 24, 2017.</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1037|| Geyserville, California||Privately owned/Francis Ford Coppola||Franklin O-335||Tucker Y-1||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Maroon/200\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|On public display in the wine tasting room at the Francis Ford Coppola Winery in Geyserville (Sonoma County), California.\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1038||Unknown||Privately owned||Franklin O-335||Cord 810/812||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Green/300\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|1038 was owned by [[Bernard Glieberman]]. It was on display in [[Shreveport, Louisiana]], while Glieberman owned the [[Shreveport Pirates]]. In 1995, creditors moved to seize the car due to Glieberman's financial problems, and Glieberman's lawyer attempted to steal the car and hide it from authorities, only to run out of gas. Glieberman was eventually allowed to keep the car.<ref>{{cite web |last= Tobas |first= Daniel |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20010208225941/http://www.shreveport.net/sports/tucker.html |url= http://www.shreveport.net/sports/tucker.html |title= The Great Tucker Caper (Or: Glieberman Schlepped Here!) |accessdate= June 29, 2011 |archivedate= February 8, 2001}}</ref> The car was sold at auction in August 2006 for $577,500 ($525,000 plus fees) and sold again in August 2008 for $1,017,500 ($925,000 plus fees).\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1039||Washington, DC||Smithsonian Institution||Franklin O-335||Tucker Y-1||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Grey(Silver)/500\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|After years hidden in Smithsonian storage, Tucker #1039 was finally placed on public display in the Museum of American History in 2011. Tucker #1039 was acquired by the Smithsonian through the U.S. Marshals Service which had previously seized the car in a 1992 narcotics arrest. Instead of selling the car, the U.S. Marshals Service decided to donate the car to the Smithsonian. Currently on loan as of February 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tucker automobile|url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/onthemove/collection/object_1182.html|work=America on the Move Collection|publisher=National Museum of American History|accessdate=February 10, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1040||Sylmar, California||The Nethercutt Museum<br/>was auctioned by Sotheby\u2019s on January 18 2019, going for $1.6 million.||Franklin O-335||Tucker Y-1||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Beige/400, now Waltz blue\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1041||California||Privately owned||Franklin O-335||Cord 810/812||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Black/100\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|Tucker #1041 was sold at the Clars Auction on June 7, 2009 for $750,000 ($765,000 with fees).\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1042||Memphis, Tennessee (Last seen)||Abandoned/Destroyed/Lost ||Franklin O-335||Tuckermatic R-1-2||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Maroon/600\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|Car #1042 was sold at the Tucker auction without an engine. Rumors exist that it was used in a \"Bash a Tucker\" fundraiser in the 1950s or may have been hauled off from its storage location by a disgruntled renter. Its location was unknown until 1960 when it was reportedly found abandoned along the banks of the Mississippi River in Memphis, Tennessee, totally destroyed. A Memphis policeman took possession of the remains, but they were later stolen from his property. Most of the Tuckermatic transmission was found and is currently located at the AACA Museum in Hershey, Pennsylvania.\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1043||Arizona||Privately owned||Franklin O-335||Unknown||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Waltz Blue/200\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|Tucker #1043 was sold at the [[Barrett-Jackson]] Auction in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]] on January 21, 2012 for $2,915,000, presumably the highest sale of a Tucker '48 sedan to date.<ref name=\"BARRETT\">[http://www.barrett-jackson.com/Events/Event/Details/1948-TUCKER-TORPEDO--115982 Barrett-Jackson, 1948 Tucker Torpedo, #1043], Retrieved March 24, 2017.</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1044||Roslyn, New York||Privately owned/Howard Kroplick||Franklin O-335||Cord 810/812||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Green/300\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|Tucker #1044 was sold at RM Sotheby's Auction in Arizona on January 19, 2017 for $1,347,500 to current owner Howard Kroplick.<ref name=\"AUCTION2\">[http://www.rmsothebys.com/az17/arizona/lots/1948-tucker-48/1650652 RM Sotheby's Auctions - 1948 Tucker 48, #1044], Retrieved March 24, 2017.</ref> The car, which had been painted a Root Beer Brown, was restored to its original color in 2018. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vanderbiltcupraces.com/blog/article/on_the_road_to_pebble_the_first_video_of_the_newly_painted_tucker_1044|title=Vanderbilt Cup Races - Blog - On the Road to Pebble: The First Video of the Newly Painted Tucker 1044|website=www.vanderbiltcupraces.com|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1045||Melbourne, Australia||Privately owned||Franklin O-335||Tucker Y-1||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Grey(Silver)/500\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|Tucker #1045 was sold at RM Auctions Sports & Classics of Monterey on August 13, 2010 for $1,127,500.<ref name=\"AUCTION3\">[http://www.rmsothebys.com/mo10/sports--classics-of-monterey/lots/1948-tucker-48-4dr-sedan/500486 RM Sotheby's Auctions - 1948 Tucker 48, #1045], Retrieved March 24, 2017.</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1046||California||Privately owned||Franklin O-335 (original) / Oldsmobile Rocket 88 / Mercury 390CID||Cord||Rubber Torsion Tube 2 (Original)/Removed for front engine conversion||Maroon/600\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|This car was converted to a front-engine Oldsmobile drive train in the 1950s by Nick Jenin for his daughter. It was converted again in the 1960s to a 1964 Mercury Monterey chassis with 390 CID front engine. Sold on eBay for $202,700 (8/20/07) and reportedly returned to original specifications, including a correct Tucker engine.\n|-\n| 1047||Hickory Corners, Michigan||[[Gilmore Car Museum]]||Franklin O-335||Cord 810/812||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Waltz Blue/200\n|-\n| 1048||Hartford, Wisconsin||Privately owned||Franklin O-335|| * Originally a Borg-Warner 3 speed automatic was installed at the factory for testing. Later, this car was sold at the factory auction WITHOUT a transmission installed. It is VERY possible a Y-1 was installed when the car was completed privately. ||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Green/300\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1049||California||Privately owned||Franklin O-335||Tucker Y-1||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Waltz Blue/200\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"|Tucker #1049 was sold at RM Sotheby's Auction in [[Monaco]] on May 14, 2016 for \u20ac1,344,000 (approximately $1,519,850).<ref name=\"AUCTION\">[http://rmsothebys.com/mc16/monaco/lots/1948-tucker-48/1079055 RM Sotheby's Auctions - 1948 Tucker 48, #1049], Retrieved March 24, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"EXCHANGE\">{{cite web|title=Euro (EUR) To United States Dollar (USD) Exchange Rate on 14 May 2016|url= http://eur.fxexchangerate.com/usd-2016_05_14-exchange-rates-history.html|website=eur.fxexchangerate.com|publisher=FxexchangeRate.com|date=May 14, 2016|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1050||[[San Marcos, Texas]]||[[Dick's Classic Garage]]||Franklin O-335||Cord 810/812||Rubber Torsion Tube 2||Maroon/600\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"| Lowest mileage Tucker with 0.4 miles on the odometer.\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+  '''Incomplete Tucker Cars Chassis #1051-1058 Completed after leaving the factory or Parted out'''\n|-\n! Chassis Number\n! Location\n! Owner\n! Engine\n! Transmission\n! Front Suspension Version\n! Original Body Color/Paint Code\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1051||Butler, New Jersey||Privately owned||Franklin O-335||Unknown||Unknown||dark red\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"| Tucker 1051 was not completed at the Tucker factory, so it is not technically considered one of the original 51 cars (prototype + 50). The car was purchased at the Tucker auction in an incomplete state, and was finished in the late 1980s using leftover Tucker parts and fiberglass replica doors.  The chassis used to complete #1051 is actually numbered #1054.<ref name=\"blog.hemmings.com\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1052||Aurora, Indiana||Privately owned||Franklin O-335||Tucker Y-1||Unknown||dark red\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"| Tucker 1052 was not completed at the Tucker factory, so it is also not technically considered one of the original 51 cars (prototype + 50).  #1052 was a test chassis used at the factory for testing automatic transmission designs.  The car consisted of only the chassis, driveline and suspension, dash and seats.  The car was completed in 2015 by Tucker Enthusiast John Schuler using NOS (New Old Stock) parts he collected over many years, along with front sheetmetal sourced from car #1018.  Reproduction floorpans, roof and rear doors were used.<ref name=\"blog.hemmings.com\"/>\n|-\n| 1053||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1054||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"| The chassis of car #1054 may have been used to complete car #1051.<ref name=\"blog.hemmings.com\"/>\n|-\n| 1055||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown\n|-\n| 1056||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1057||Unknown||Privately owned||Franklin O-335||Cord 610/812||Unknown||Waltz Blue/200\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\"| #1057 was the prototype being worked on by Tucker designer Alex Tremulis for the 1949 model year.  It was one of eight incomplete body shells (believed to be #1051-1058) left on the assembly line at the time the Tucker plant was closed.  Photos from the factory show #1057 was being built with a \"wrap around rear window\" as one of the 1949 year design changes and is the only 1949 model.  But #1057 was later converted to a convertible, whether at the factory or later is unknown. \n|-\n| 1058||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown||Unknown\n|-\n|}\n\n== Replica vehicles ==\nIn 1997, Rob Ida Automotive started work on a replica of the Tucker '48 Sedan, which culminated in the release and marketing of the 2001 Ida Automotive New Tucker '48. This replica faithfully recreates the Tucker's external bodywork, but is built on a hotrod chassis with resin-infused plastic body panels. The paint and wheels reflect modern hotrod styling, and the interior is fully modern. It is powered by a mid-mounted Cadillac [[Northstar engine series|Northstar V8]]. Claimed performance is 0\u201360 in 7 seconds, with a top speed in excess of {{convert|120|mph|kph|abbr=on}}. Ida has built three cars.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Matras|first=John|title=Ida Automotive New Tucker 48|journal=Car and Driver|date=July 2001|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/ida-automotive-new-tucker-48-specialty-file| accessdate= February 10, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==NASCAR==\n\nSeveral Tuckers were entered in the [[NASCAR]] Grand National series in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web |last= Schutta |first= Mike |date= March 1, 2012 |title= Racing Rarity |work= Hemmings Motor News |url= http://www.hemmings.com/hcc/stories/2012/03/01/hmn_feature1.html |accessdate= August 18, 2013}})</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Tucker: The Man and His Dream]]''\n* [[List of defunct United States automobile manufacturers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Tucker 48}}\n* [http://www.tuckerclub.org TuckerClub.org Official Tucker Automobile Club of America Website - Information about the cars, including the locations of all extant examples]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050216025208/http://www.hfmgv.org/exhibits/showroom/1948/tucker.html www.htmgv.org Henry Ford Museum Tucker Exhibit]\n* [http://www.robidaconcepts.com/ RobIdaConcepts.com The Ida Automotive New Tucker '48 and Lower '48]\n* [http://jalopnik.com/335574/tucker-48 Tucker 48 Jalopnik Fantasy Garage]\n* [http://sketchup.google.com/3dwarehouse/details?mid=d8d6fad71743311e108275b7e87f057e&prevstart=0 Tucker Torpedo Automobile 1948 3D model of the Tucker]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110310100307/http://forums.aaca.org/f169/tucker-1010-going-auction-291610.html Antique Automobile Club thread about the auction of Tucker #1010]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090130093015/http://chuckstoyland.com/potpourri/coololdcars/ Short lived/Odd vehicle collection from Chuck's Toyland]\n*[http://huntsvillerewound.com/HSVkellercar.htm Huntsville Rewound feature about Keller Automobiles (18 made/3 exist)]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tucker}}\n[[Category:1948 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Car manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Motor vehicle manufacturers based in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by boxer engines]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by aircraft engines]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1948]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n[[Category:Rear-engined vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by rear-mounted 6-cylinder engines]]\n", "name_user": "73.134.27.23", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eplz forgive me)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tucker_48"}
{"title_page": "List of Minangkabau clans", "text_new": "The following is a list of [[Minangkabau clans]].<ref>[http://urangminang.com/sejarah-adat-budaya/18-suku-dalam-etnis-minangkabau Suku dalam Etnis Minangkabau]</ref>\n\nThe clans are listed in alphabetical order. The clans in '''bold''' indicate the parent clans with their sub-clans are written in ''italic''.\n\n== List of Minangkabau clans ==\n=== A ===\n* Ampu\n* Anak Aceh - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah>Ibrahim Abdullah, ''[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:OCB8RtNwIBkJ:malaycivilization.ukm.my/idc/groups/portal_aperpatih/documents/ukmpd/adat_00252.pdf+suku+anak+melaka+negeri+sembilan&hl=id&gl=id&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEEShWUJegGKT3KkGStaiVg6jU2tdyY8BvIuSvniwTvbEGM2yRuQ_W5ki9bN5146r0ZLCUV4fapvIDuSp7xtacMbmEHxELXeKiaNYqoLAABix9LkKau_UNJO5acDIK5Aa9aEAFumW3&sig=AHIEtbSvybX6ZUg6YIIOYK-9kfIa1OIa7w Struktur Suku di Rembau]'', dalam Norazit Selat (editor), ''Negeri Sembilan: dahulu dan sekarang''. Kuala Lumpur: Persatuan Muzium Malaysia, Muzium Negara, 1990.</ref>\n* Anak Malako - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n=== B ===\n* Banuhampu\n* Banuo\n* Bapayuang\n* Baraguang\n* Barajo\n* Batu Balang - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* '''Batu Hampar''' (abbreviated as '''Tompar''', including ''Batu Hampar Minangkabau, Batu Hampar Patani'') - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Batu Kambiang\n* Batu Pahek\n* Bawang\n* '''Bandang''' (including ''Bandang Ateh Bukik, Bandang Rumah Baru, Bandang Salek'')\n* '''Bicu''' (including ''Bicu Sajo, Bicu Sipanjang'')\n* '''Biduando''' (abbreviated as '''Dondo''', including ''Biduando Lelo Maharajo Warih Jakun, Biduando Sadia Rajo Warih Jao, Biduando Sari Maharajo, Biduando Tampin'') - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Bilang Ijin\n* '''Bodi''' (including ''Bodi Batino, Bodi Caniago, Bodi Jantan'')\n=== C ===\n* '''Caniago''' (including ''Caniago Baruah, Caniago Bawah, Caniago Nan Baranam, Caniago Sabarang, Caniago Ujuang'')\n* Cocoh\n* Cubadak\n* Cupak\n=== D ===\n* Datuak Kitan Putiah\n* '''Dalimo''' (including ''Dalimo Panjang'')\n* Dendang\n* '''Depati''' (including ''Depati Manggumi, Depati Mudo, Depati Sakungkuang'')\n* Durian nan Limo Ruang\n=== G ===\n* Gantiang\n* Guci\n=== H ===\n* Hapai nan Tigo Ibu\n=== J ===\n* '''Jambak''' (including ''Jambak nan Balimo'')\n=== K ===\n* Kabaru\n* Kalumpang\n* '''Kampai''' (including ''Kampai Aia Angek nan Baranam, Kampai nan Duo Puluah Ampek, Kampai Tangah Niua Gadiang nan Baranam'')\n* Kampuang Dalam\n* Kampuang Gadang\n* Karak\n* Kinari\n* Korong Gadang\n* '''Koto''' (including ''Koto Dalimo, Koto Diateh, Koto Kaciak, Koto Kaciak Ampek Paruaik, Koto Kampuang, Koto Kerambil, Koto Piliang, Koto Sipanjang'')\n* '''Kutianyia''' (including ''Kutianyia Baruah, Kutianyia Ikua Pancah, Kutianyia Kampuang Tangah, Kutianyia Kapalo Bancah, Kutianyia Kapalo Labuah, Kutianyia Pitopang, Kutianyia Tabel Lintang'')\n=== L ===\n* Laweh\n* Lubuak\n* Lubuak Batuang\n=== M ===\n* Maih\n* '''Malayu''' (including ''Malayu Badarah Putiah, Malayu Baduak, Malayu Balai, Malayu Baruah, Malayu Bandang, Malayu Bongsu, Malayu Basa, Malayu Bungo, Malayu Cikarau, Malayu Gandang Parak, Malayu Kumbuak Candi, Malayu Kumbuak Harum, Malayu Lampai, Malayu Lua, Malayu Panjang, Malayu Patar, Malayu Siat, Malayu Talang, Malayu Tobo, Malayu Tangah'')\n* '''Mandaliko''' (including ''Mandaliko Budur, Mandaliko Tangah Gadang, Mandaliko Tangah Patah'')\n* '''Mandehiliang''' (including ''Mandehiliang Panai, Mandehiliang Gadang, Madehiliang Subarang'')\n* Mansiang\n* Marajo Basa\n* Marajo Lelo\n* Mejan\n* Mungka - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n=== N ===\n* Nangkapuh (Kandang Kapuh)\n* Nan Sambilan\n=== P ===\n* Paga Cancang\n* Pamangku\n* Panampuang\n* Pangian Kaciak\n* Panyalai\n* '''Parik''' (including ''Parik Cancang'')\n* Parindari\n* '''Payobada''' (including ''Payobada Ateh, Payobada Kubang, Payobada Sungkai, Payobada Kunpanjang'')\n* '''Piliang''' (including ''Piliang Barum, Piliang Bongsu, Piliang Cocoh, Piliang Dalam, Piliang Koto, Piliang Koto Kaciak, Piliang Laweh, Piliang Patar, Piliang Sani, Piliang Sati'')\n* Pisang\n* '''Pitopang''' (including ''Pitopang Basah, Pitopang Darek, Pitopang Dibawah, Pitopang Ditangah, Pitopang Gadang, Pitopang Koto Tuo, Pitopang Lado, Pitopang Rumah Panjang'')\n* Panggang\n* Payakumbuh - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Pungkuik\n=== R ===\n* Rabu\n* Rio Mudo\n=== S ===\n* Saibi\n* '''Salo''' (including ''Salo-Kutianyia, Salo-Caniago'')\n* Sambilan Niniak\n* Saratuih\n* '''Sari Lamak''' (abbreviated as '''Solomak''', including ''Sari Lamak Minangkabau, Sari Lamak Pahang'') - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Sawah Jauah\n* Seboang\n* Sialiali\n* '''Sikumbang''' (including ''Sikumbang Ampek Ibu, Sikumbang Gadang'')\n* Simabua\n* '''Simalanggang''' (including ''Simalanggang Minangkabau, Simalanggang Naning, Simalanggang Ampek Ibu, Simalanggang Minangkabau Kandung, Simalanggang Rokan, Simalanggang Panglima Bongsu'') - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Sumagek\n* Sunan Sarajo\n* Sungai Napar\n* Supanjang\n=== T ===\n* Tabek Gadang\n* Tali Kincia\n* Tanah Data - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Tangah Sawah\n* Tanian\n* Tanika\n* '''Tanjuang''' (including ''Tanjuang Batu, Tanjuang Gadang, Tanjuang Talago'')\n* Tapi Aia\n* Tigo Batu - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Tigo Lareh\n* Tigo Niniak - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Minangkabau clans]]\n*[[Minangkabau Highlands]]\n*[[Minangkabau language]]\n*[[Minangkabau people]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ethno-stub}}\n{{Asia-ethno-group-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The following is a list of [[Minangkabau clans]].<ref>[http://urangminang.com/sejarah-adat-budaya/18-suku-dalam-etnis-minangkabau Suku dalam Etnis Minangkabau]</ref>\n\nThe clans are listed in alphabetical order. The clans in '''bold''' indicate the parent clans with their sub-clans are written in ''italic''.\n\n== List of Minangkabau clans ==\n\n=== A ===\n* Ampu\n* Anak Aceh - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah>Ibrahim Abdullah, ''[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:OCB8RtNwIBkJ:malaycivilization.ukm.my/idc/groups/portal_aperpatih/documents/ukmpd/adat_00252.pdf+suku+anak+melaka+negeri+sembilan&hl=id&gl=id&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEEShWUJegGKT3KkGStaiVg6jU2tdyY8BvIuSvniwTvbEGM2yRuQ_W5ki9bN5146r0ZLCUV4fapvIDuSp7xtacMbmEHxELXeKiaNYqoLAABix9LkKau_UNJO5acDIK5Aa9aEAFumW3&sig=AHIEtbSvybX6ZUg6YIIOYK-9kfIa1OIa7w Struktur Suku di Rembau]'', dalam Norazit Selat (editor), ''Negeri Sembilan: dahulu dan sekarang''. Kuala Lumpur: Persatuan Muzium Malaysia, Muzium Negara, 1990.</ref>\n* Anak Malako - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n\n=== B ===\n* Banuhampu\n* Banuo\n* Bapayuang\n* Baraguang\n* Barajo\n* Batu Balang - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* '''Batu Hampar''' (abbreviated as '''Tompar''', including ''Batu Hampar Minangkabau, Batu Hampar Patani'') - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Batu Kambiang\n* Batu Pahek\n* Bawang\n* '''Bandang''' (including ''Bandang Ateh Bukik, Bandang Rumah Baru, Bandang Salek'')\n* '''Bicu''' (including ''Bicu Sajo, Bicu Sipanjang'')\n* '''Biduando''' (abbreviated as '''Dondo''', including ''Biduando Lelo Maharajo Warih Jakun, Biduando Sadia Rajo Warih Jao, Biduando Sari Maharajo, Biduando Tampin'') - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Bilang Ijin\n* '''Bodi''' (including ''Bodi Batino, Bodi Caniago, Bodi Jantan'')\n\n=== C ===\n* '''Caniago''' (including ''Caniago Baruah, Caniago Bawah, Caniago Nan Baranam, Caniago Sabarang, Caniago Ujuang'')\n* Cocoh\n* Cubadak\n* Cupak\n\n=== D ===\n* Datuak Kitan Putiah\n* '''Dalimo''' (including ''Dalimo Panjang'')\n* Dendang\n* '''Depati''' (including ''Depati Manggumi, Depati Mudo, Depati Sakungkuang'')\n* Durian Nan Limo Ruang\n\n=== G ===\n* Gantiang\n* Guci\n\n=== H ===\n* Hapai Nan Tigo Ibu\n\n=== J ===\n* '''Jambak''' (including ''Jambak nan Balimo'')\n\n=== K ===\n* Kabaru\n* Kalumpang\n* '''Kampai''' (including ''Kampai Aia Angek Nan Baranam, Kampai Nan Duo Puluah Ampek, Kampai Tangah Niua Gadiang Nan Baranam'')\n* Kampuang Dalam\n* Kampuang Gadang\n* Karak\n* Kinari\n* Korong Gadang\n* '''Koto''' (including ''Koto Dalimo, Koto Diateh, Koto Kaciak, Koto Kaciak Ampek Paruaik, Koto Kampuang, Koto Kerambil, Koto Piliang, Koto Sipanjang'')\n* '''Kutianyia''' (including ''Kutianyia Baruah, Kutianyia Ikua Pancah, Kutianyia Kampuang Tangah, Kutianyia Kapalo Bancah, Kutianyia Kapalo Labuah, Kutianyia Pitopang, Kutianyia Tabel Lintang'')\n\n=== L ===\n* Laweh\n* Lubuak\n* Lubuak Batuang\n\n=== M ===\n* Maih\n* '''Malayu''' (including ''Malayu Badarah Putiah, Malayu Baduak, Malayu Balai, Malayu Baruah, Malayu Bandang, Malayu Bongsu, Malayu Basa, Malayu Bungo, Malayu Cikarau, Malayu Gandang Parak, Malayu Kumbuak Candi, Malayu Kumbuak Harum, Malayu Lampai, Malayu Lua, Malayu Panjang, Malayu Patar, Malayu Siat, Malayu Talang, Malayu Tobo, Malayu Tangah'')\n* '''Mandaliko''' (including ''Mandaliko Budur, Mandaliko Tangah Gadang, Mandaliko Tangah Patah'')\n* '''Mandehiliang''' (including ''Mandehiliang Panai, Mandehiliang Gadang, Madehiliang Subarang'')\n* Mansiang\n* Marajo Bosa\n* Marajo Lelo\n* Mejan\n* Mungka - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n\n=== N ===\n* Nangkapuh (Kandang Kapuh)\n* Nan Sambilan\n\n=== P ===\n* Paga Cancang\n* Pamangku\n* Panampuang\n* Pangian Kaciak\n* Panyalai\n* '''Parik''' (including ''Parik Cancang'')\n* Parindari\n* '''Payobada''' (including ''Payobada Ateh, Payobada Kubang, Payobada Sungkai, Payobada Kunpanjang'')\n* '''Piliang''' (including ''Piliang Barum, Piliang Bongsu, Piliang Cocoh, Piliang Dalam, Piliang Koto, Piliang Koto Kaciak, Piliang Laweh, Piliang Patar, Piliang Sani, Piliang Sati'')\n* Pisang\n* '''Pitopang''' (including ''Pitopang Basah, Pitopang Darek, Pitopang Dibawah, Pitopang Ditangah, Pitopang Gadang, Pitopang Koto Tuo, Pitopang Lado, Pitopang Rumah Panjang'')\n* Panggang\n* Payakumbuh - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Pungkuik\n\n=== R ===\n* Rabu\n* Rio Mudo\n\n=== S ===\n* Saibi\n* '''Salo''' (including ''Salo-Kutianyia, Salo-Caniago'')\n* Sambilan Niniak\n* Saratuih\n* '''Sari Lamak''' (abbreviated as '''Solomak''', including ''Sari Lamak Minangkabau, Sari Lamak Pahang'') - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Sawah Jauah\n* Seboang\n* Sialiali\n* '''Sikumbang''' (including ''Sikumbang Ampek Ibu, Sikumbang Gadang'')\n* Simabua\n* '''Simalanggang''' (including ''Simalanggang Minangkabau, Simalanggang Naning, Simalanggang Ampek Ibu, Simalanggang Minangkabau Kandung, Simalanggang Rokan, Simalanggang Panglima Bongsu'') - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Sumagek\n* Sunan Sarajo\n* Sungai Napar\n* Supanjang\n\n=== T ===\n* Tabek Gadang\n* Tali Kincia\n* Tanah Data - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Tangah Sawah\n* Tanian\n* Tanika\n* '''Tanjuang''' (including ''Tanjuang Batu, Tanjuang Gadang, Tanjuang Talago'')\n* Tapi Aia\n* Tigo Batu - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n* Tigo Lareh\n* Tigo Niniak - in [[Negeri Sembilan]]<ref name=Abdullah/>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Minangkabau clans]]\n*[[Minangkabau Highlands]]\n*[[Minangkabau language]]\n*[[Minangkabau people]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ethno-stub}}\n{{Asia-ethno-group-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Umar Selon", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eList of Minangkabau clans", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Minangkabau_clans"}
{"title_page": "John Stanbridge", "text_new": "{{No footnotes|date=January 2020}}\n'''John Stanbridge''' (1463\u20131510) was an English [[Philologist|grammarian]] and [[schoolmaster]].\n\nHe was born in [[Upper Heyford, Northamptonshire|Heyford, Northamptonshire]] and educated in [[Winchester College]]. In 1480 he went to [[New College, Oxford]] and stayed until 1486, when he joined the staff of the newly founded [[Magdalen College School, Oxford|Magdalen College School]], founded by [[William Waynflete]]. Stanbridge became headmaster in 1488, following the death of [[John Anwykyll]].\n\nHe is best remembered for the series of educational books which he wrote and edited:\n\n*''Accidence'' (c.1505)\n*''Parvulorum institutio'' (c.1507)\n*''Gradus comparationum'' together with ''Sum es fui'' (c.1509)\n*''Vulgaria'' (c.1509)\n*''Vocabula'' (1510)\n\nThese works were important as they were among the first in England to incorporate humanist educational principles and standards of Latin with the older style of teaching materials.\n\n==References==\n*{{cite DNB|wstitle=Stanbridge, John|volume=53}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://oxoniensia.org/volumes/2003/martins.pdf ''John Stanbridge, Early Tudor Teacher and Grammarian of Oxford and Banbury''], PDF From [http://oxoniensia.org \"Oxoniensia\"] - Website of The annual journal of Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society (OAHS).\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanbridge, John}}\n[[Category:1463 births]]\n[[Category:1510 deaths]]\n[[Category:15th-century English people]]\n[[Category:16th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:16th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:15th-century educators]]\n[[Category:16th-century English educators]]\n[[Category:Education writers]]\n[[Category:Schoolteachers from Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Grammarians from England]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n\n{{England-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{No footnotes|date=January 2020}}\n'''John Stanbridge''' (1463\u20131510) was an English [[Philologist|grammarian]] and [[schoolmaster]].\n\nHe was born in [[Heyford, Northamptonshire]]{{Dab needed|date=January 2020}} and educated in [[Winchester College]]. In 1480 he went to [[New College, Oxford]] and stayed until 1486, when he joined the staff of the newly founded [[Magdalen College School, Oxford|Magdalen College School]], founded by [[William Waynflete]]. Stanbridge became headmaster in 1488, following the death of [[John Anwykyll]].\n\nHe is best remembered for the series of educational books which he wrote and edited:\n\n*''Accidence'' (c.1505)\n*''Parvulorum institutio'' (c.1507)\n*''Gradus comparationum'' together with ''Sum es fui'' (c.1509)\n*''Vulgaria'' (c.1509)\n*''Vocabula'' (1510)\n\nThese works were important as they were among the first in England to incorporate humanist educational principles and standards of Latin with the older style of teaching materials.\n\n==References==\n*{{cite DNB|wstitle=Stanbridge, John|volume=53}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://oxoniensia.org/volumes/2003/martins.pdf ''John Stanbridge, Early Tudor Teacher and Grammarian of Oxford and Banbury''], PDF From [http://oxoniensia.org \"Oxoniensia\"] - Website of The annual journal of Oxfordshire Architectural and Historical Society (OAHS).\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanbridge, John}}\n[[Category:1463 births]]\n[[Category:1510 deaths]]\n[[Category:15th-century English people]]\n[[Category:16th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:16th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:15th-century educators]]\n[[Category:16th-century English educators]]\n[[Category:Education writers]]\n[[Category:Schoolteachers from Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Grammarians from England]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n\n{{England-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHeyford(link changed toUpper Heyford, Northamptonshire) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Stanbridge"}
{"title_page": "Hugo Macedo", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{UPE|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Hugo Macedo\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = Hugo Macedo\n| birth_name  = Hugo Miguel Magalh\u00e3es Macedo\n| birth_date  = November 17, 1982\n| birth_place = [[Arco de Ba\u00falhe]], [[Braga]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Portugal]]\n| ethnicity   = \n| other_names = \n| education   = [[Universidade Nova de Lisboa]], [[Imperial College London]]\n| alma_mater  = \n| occupation  = [[Engineering technologist]]\n| known_for   = Founder and CEO of Smart Separations Ltd\n}}\n\n'''Hugo Miguel Magalh\u00e3es Macedo''' (born November 17, 1982) is a Portuguese-born [[Engineering technologist]] known as the Founder and CEO of Smart Separations Ltd.<ref name=\"TG\">[https://www.theguardian.com/small-business-network/2015/apr/14/startup-of-the-year-2014-smart-separations \"Startup of the year 2014: Smart Separations\"], ''theguardian.com'', April 14, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Arco de Ba\u00falhe]], [[Braga]], [[Portugal]], Macedo holds a [[Licentiate (degree)|Licenciatura degree]] in [[Chemical Engineering]] from the [[Universidade Nova de Lisboa]] (2000 \u2013 2006). He also holds a Diploma in [[Tissue Engineering]] from the [[Imperial College London]] (2006 \u2013 2011). He equally holds a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in Tissue Engineering from the same Imperial College London (2011).<ref name=\"PP\">[http://parsuk.pt/site/about-us/who-are-we/executive-committee-bio/ \"Hugo Macedo - Vice President - Imperial College London\"], ''parsuk.pt'',.</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nMacedo began a career in technology engineering while doing his PhD in Tissue Engineering at the Imperial College, London in 2011. He explored research areas such as chemical engineering, [[Stem cell|stem cell technology]], [[Membrane technology]], [[Quantum hydrodynamics|hydrodynamics]], [[Cell culture|stem cell culture]] and [[Bioprocess|bio-processing]], human blood production, and a lot more.<ref name=\"SP\">[http://www.superinteressante.pt/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2518:fabricas-de-sangue&catid=3:artigos&Itemid=77 \"F\u00e1bricas de sangue\"], ''superinteressante.pt'',.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Macedo created the first [[Hollow fiber bioreactor|3D hollow fibre bioreactor]] meant for the production of human red blood cells. This got patented as a system design and also featured in [[Metro (magazine)|Metro Magazine]] and on the cover page of the November 2011 edition of The Chemical Engineer (TCE) Magazine.<ref name=\"SP\"/>\n\nBetween 2012 and 2013, Macedo was the Vice-President of PARSUK; the Portuguese Association of Researchers and Students in the UK.<ref name=\"PP\"/> In 2013, he also founded Smart Separations Ltd; a technology company that has patented a new filtration technology that overcomes the limitations of existing microsieves. He is currently the CEO of the company and also holds 5 patents.<ref name=\"TG\"/>\n\nMacedo is a technology writer. He wrote and published a book chapter captioned  ''Hollow fibre membrane bioreactor technology for tissue engineering and stem cell therapy, In: Comprehensive Membrane Science and Engineering''.<ref>[http://store.elsevier.com/Comprehensive-Membrane-Science-and-Engineering/isbn-9780444532046/ \"Hollow fibre membrane bioreactor technology for tissue engineering and stem cell therapy, In: Comprehensive Membrane Science and Engineering (Eds. E Drioli and L Giorno)\"], ''store.elsevier.com'', July 9, 2010.</ref> He has also written several research papers, journals, and conference papers.<ref>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/citations?user=OPtoGRUAAAAJ&hl=pt-PT \"Hugo Macedo CEO\"], ''scholar.google.co.uk'',.</ref><ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Hugo_Macedo2/publications \"Hugo Macedo Smart Separations Ltd\"], ''researchgate.net'',.</ref>\n\n==Awards/recognitions==\n* First prize in the Chemical Engineering PhD Symposium 2010 at the Chemical Engineering Department, Imperial College London. March 2010<ref>[http://www.imperial.ac.uk/engineering/departments/chemical-engineering/courses/postgraduate/phd/symposium/ \"Chemical Engineering PhD Symposium 2015\"], ''imperial.ac.uk'',.</ref>\n* Finalist at the Biotechnology Young Entrepreneurs Scheme (YES) 2010 at EPSRC and University of Nottingham, with the company HemaStem; London. 2010.<ref name=\"PP\"/>\n* STARTUP OF THE YEAR 2014 - Smart Separations Ltd, April 2015 by [[The Guardian]]<ref name=\"TG\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.hugomacedo.com}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macedo, Hugo}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Imperial College London]]\n[[Category:Portuguese businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Portuguese chief executives]]\n[[Category:Portuguese male writers]]\n[[Category:Technicians]]\n[[Category:Universidade Nova de Lisboa alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{UPE|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Hugo Macedo\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = Hugo Macedo\n| birth_name  = Hugo Miguel Magalh\u00e3es Macedo\n| birth_date  = November 17, 1982\n| birth_place = [[Arco de Ba\u00falhe]], [[Braga]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Portugal]]\n| ethnicity   = \n| other_names = \n| education   = [[Universidade Nova de Lisboa]], [[Imperial College London]]\n| alma_mater  = \n| occupation  = [[Engineering technologist]]\n| known_for   = Founder and CEO of Smart Separations Ltd\n}}\n\n'''Hugo Miguel Magalh\u00e3es Macedo''' (born November 17, 1982) is a Portuguese-born [[Engineering technologist]] known as the Founder and CEO of Smart Separations Ltd.<ref name=\"TG\">[https://www.theguardian.com/small-business-network/2015/apr/14/startup-of-the-year-2014-smart-separations \"Startup of the year 2014: Smart Separations\"], ''theguardian.com'', April 14, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Arco de Ba\u00falhe]], [[Braga]], [[Portugal]], Macedo holds a [[Licentiate (degree)|Licenciatura degree]] in [[Chemical Engineering]] from the [[Universidade Nova de Lisboa]] (2000 \u2013 2006). He also holds a Diploma in [[Tissue Engineering]] from the [[Imperial College London]] (2006 \u2013 2011). He equally holds a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in Tissue Engineering from the same Imperial College London (2011).<ref name=\"PP\">[http://parsuk.pt/site/about-us/who-are-we/executive-committee-bio/ \"Hugo Macedo - Vice President - Imperial College London\"], ''parsuk.pt'',.</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nMacedo began a career in technology engineering while doing his PhD in Tissue Engineering at the Imperial College, London in 2011. He explored research areas such as chemical engineering, [[Stem cell|stem cell technology]], [[Membrane technology]], [[Quantum hydrodynamics|hydrodynamics]], [[Cell culture|stem cell culture]] and [[Bioprocess|bio-processing]], human blood production, and a lot more.<ref name=\"SP\">[http://www.superinteressante.pt/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2518:fabricas-de-sangue&catid=3:artigos&Itemid=77 \"F\u00e1bricas de sangue\"], ''superinteressante.pt'',.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Macedo created the first [[Hollow fiber bioreactor|3D hollow fibre bioreactor]] meant for the production of human red blood cells. This got patented as a system design and also featured in [[Metro (magazine)|Metro Magazine]] and on the cover page of the November 2011 edition of The Chemical Engineer (TCE) Magazine.<ref name=\"SP\"/>\n\nBetween 2012 and 2013, Macedo was the Vice-President of PARSUK; the Portuguese Association of Researchers and Students in the UK.<ref name=\"PP\"/> In 2013, he also founded Smart Separations Ltd; a technology company that has patented a new filtration technology that overcomes the limitations of existing microsieves. He is currently the CEO of the company and also holds 5 patents.<ref name=\"TG\"/>\n\nMacedo is a technology writer. He wrote and published a book chapter captioned  ''Hollow fibre membrane bioreactor technology for tissue engineering and stem cell therapy, In: Comprehensive Membrane Science and Engineering''.<ref>[http://store.elsevier.com/Comprehensive-Membrane-Science-and-Engineering/isbn-9780444532046/ \"Hollow fibre membrane bioreactor technology for tissue engineering and stem cell therapy, In: Comprehensive Membrane Science and Engineering (Eds. E Drioli and L Giorno)\"], ''store.elsevier.com'', July 9, 2010.</ref> He has also written several research papers, journals, and conference papers.<ref>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/citations?user=OPtoGRUAAAAJ&hl=pt-PT \"Hugo Macedo CEO\"], ''scholar.google.co.uk'',.</ref><ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Hugo_Macedo2/publications \"Hugo Macedo Smart Separations Ltd\"], ''researchgate.net'',.</ref>\n\n==Awards/recognitions==\n* First prize in the Chemical Engineering PhD Symposium 2010 at the Chemical Engineering Department, Imperial College London. March 2010<ref>[http://www.imperial.ac.uk/engineering/departments/chemical-engineering/courses/postgraduate/phd/symposium/ \"Chemical Engineering PhD Symposium 2015\"], ''imperial.ac.uk'',.</ref>\n* Finalist at the Biotechnology Young Entrepreneurs Scheme (YES) 2010 at EPSRC and University of Nottingham, with the company HemaStem; London. 2010.<ref name=\"PP\"/>\n* STARTUP OF THE YEAR 2014 - Smart Separations Ltd, April 2015 by [[The Guardian]]<ref name=\"TG\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.hugomacedo.com}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macedo, Hugo}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Imperial College London]]\n[[Category:Portuguese businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Portuguese chief executives]]\n[[Category:Portuguese male writers]]\n[[Category:Technicians]]\n[[Category:Universidade Nova de Lisboa alumni]]\n",